f Honor (deceased)\n* [[Laurence Tribe]], [[Harvard]] constitutional scholar\n* [[Gaddi H. Vasquez]], former Director of the Peace Corps\n* [[Cindy S. Moelis]]\n* [[Janet Eissenstat]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20090114032514/http://www.whitehouse.gov/fellows/ White House Fellow website]\n\n{{White House Office|state=collapsed}}\n{{EOP agencies}}\n\n[[Category:Presidency of the United States]]\n[[Category:White House Office|Fellows]]\n[[Category:1964 establishments in Washington, D.C.]]\n[[Category:Fellowships]]\n", "name_user": "John of Reading", "label": "safe", "comment": "Generalfixes, updated one cited title after looking at the archive.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/White_House_Fellows"}
{"title_page": "Turda", "text_new": "{{about||the former administrative subdivision of Romania|Turda County|the village in Tulcea County|Mihai Bravu, Tulcea}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=June 2012}}\n{{More citations needed|date=February 2007}}\n{{Infobox Romanian subdivision\n|type                   = municipality\n|county                 = Cluj\n|population_total       = auto\n|official_name                  = Turda\n|image_skyline                  = 2011-IMG 4425.jpg\n|image_caption                  = Republic Square\n|image_map              = Turda jud Cluj.png\n|map_caption            = Location in Cluj County\n|coordinates                    = {{coord|46|34|N|23|47|E|region:RO_type:city|display=inline,title}}\n|image_shield                   = Turda, Cluj COA.png\n|leader_name                    = Cristian-Octavian Matei<ref>[http://primariaturda.ro/primaria-turda/conducerea-primariei/cristian-octavian-matei/ primariaturda.ro]</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.2016bec.ro/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/SIAL2016_P_Lista_Moc-2.xlsx |title=Results of the 2016 local elections |publisher=Central Electoral Bureau |accessdate=2020-04-03 |df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n|leader_party                   = PSD\n|area_total_km2                 = 91.43\n|website                        = {{url|http://primariaturda.ro/}}\n}}\n\n'''Turda''' ({{IPA-ro|\u02c8turda}}; {{lang-de|link=no|Thorenburg}}; {{lang-hu|Torda}}; {{lang-la|Potaissa}}) is a [[Municipiu|city]] in [[Cluj County]], Romania, situated on the river [[Arie\u0219]].\n\n==History==\n\n===Ancient times===\n{{See also|Potaissa (castra)}}\n[[File:Milliarum of Aiton, modern copy erected in Turda, Romania in 1993.jpg|thumb|left|''Milliarium of Aiton'', the oldest known epigraphical attestation of Potaissa&nbsp;\u2013 a copy erected in June 1993 in front of the Turda Post Office]]\nThere is evidence of human settlement in the area dating to the [[Middle Paleolithic]], some 60,000 years ago.<ref>{{in lang|ro}} [http://www.primariaturda.ro/index.php?topic=29&blank=0&pag=comuna_primitiva.htm \"Comuna primitiv\u0103\"] at the Turda City Hall site; accessed March 21, 2013</ref> The [[Dacia]]ns established a town that [[Ptolemy]] in his [[Geography (Ptolemy)|''Geography'']] calls ''Patreuissa'', which is probably a corruption of ''Patavissa'' or ''Potaissa'', the latter being more common. It was conquered by the [[Ancient Rome|Romans]], who kept the name ''Potaissa'', between AD 101 and 106, during the rule of [[Trajan]], together with parts of [[Decebal]]'s [[Dacia]].<ref>{{in lang|ro}} [http://www.primariaturda.ro/index.php?topic=29&blank=0&pag=epoca_dacica.htm \"Epoca dacic\u0103\"] at the Turda City Hall site; accessed March 21, 2013</ref>\n\nThe name Potaissa is first recorded on a Roman [[milliarium]] discovered in 1758 in the nearby [[Aiton, Cluj|Aiton]] commune.<ref name=\"roman\">Lazarovici ''et al.'' 1997, pp. 202\u20133 (6.2 Cluj in the Old and Ancient Epochs)</ref>\n\n[[File:2006 0602Turda0088Potaissa.jpg|thumb|left|[[Roman bath]] at [[Potaissa (castra)|Castra Potaissa]]]]\n[[Milliarium of Aiton]] is an ancient Roman milestone dating from 108 AD, shortly after the [[Roman conquest of Dacia]], and showing the construction of the road from Potaissa to Napoca, by demand of the Emperor Trajan. It indicates the distance of {{convert|10000|ft|m}} (P.M.X.) to Potaissa. This is the first [[epigraphical]] attestation of the settlements of Potaissa and [[Napoca (ancient city)|Napoca]] in [[Roman Dacia]].\n\nThe complete inscription is: \"''Imp(erator)/ Caesar Nerva/ Traianus Aug(ustus)/ Germ(anicus) Dacicus/ pontif(ex) maxim(us)/ ''(sic)'' pot(estate) XII co(n)s(ul) V/ imp(erator) VI p(ater) p(atriae) fecit/ per coh(ortem) I Fl(aviam) Vlp(iam)/ Hisp(anam) mil(liariam) c(ivium) R(omanorum) eq(uitatam)/ a Potaissa Napo/cam / m(ilia) p(assuum) X''\". It was recorded in the ''[[Corpus Inscriptionum Latinarum]]'', vol.III, the 1627, Berlin, 1863.\n\nThis milliarium is an attestation of the road known to be built by ''[[Cohors I Hispanorum miliaria]]''.<ref>{{cite web |title=ARCHAEOLOGICAL REPERTORY OF ROMANIA. Archive Of The ''Vasile Parvan'' Institute Of Archaeology \u2013 Site Location Index |url=http://www.cimec.ro/scripts/arh/rar-index/sel.asp?nr=13&lang=en&nrsel=0&IDRap=1432#Lk1432 |accessdate=September 20, 2014 }}</ref>\n\nThe [[castrum]] established was named ''Potaissa'' too and became a [[municipium]], then a [[Colonia (Roman)|colonia]]. Potaissa was the basecamp of the [[Legio V Macedonica|Legio V ''Macedonica'']] from 166 to 274.\n\nThe [[Salina Turda|Potaissa salt mines]] were worked in the area since prehistoric times.\n\n===Middle Ages===\n{{See also|Transylvania in the Middle Ages}}\nAfter the [[Kingdom of Hungary|Hungarian]] conquest, the [[Salina Turda|Turda salt mines]] were first mentioned in 1075. They were closed in 1932 but have recently been reopened for tourism.\n\n[[Transylvanian Saxons|Saxons]] settled in the area in the 12th century. The town was destroyed during the Tartar invasion in 1241\u20131242. [[Andrew III of Hungary]] gave royal privileges to the settlement. These privileges were later confirmed by the [[Louis I of Hungary|Angevins of Hungary]].{{Citation needed|date=March 2010}}\n\nThe Hungarian Diet was held here in 1467, by [[Matthias Corvinus]]. Later, in the 16th century, Turda was often the residence of the [[Transylvanian Diet]], too. After the [[Battle of Moh\u00e1cs]], the city became part of the [[Eastern Hungarian Kingdom]] and since 1570 the [[Principality of Transylvania (1570\u20131711)|Principality of Transylvania]]. The 1558 Diet of Turda declared free practice of both the Catholic and [[Lutheranism|Lutheran]] religions. In 1563 the Diet also accepted the [[Calvinist]] religion, and in 1568 it extended freedom to all religions, declaring that \"It is not allowed to anybody to intimidate anybody with captivity or expelling for his religion\"&nbsp;\u2013 a freedom unusual in medieval Europe. This [[Edict of Turda]] is the first attempt at legislating general religious freedom in Christian Europe (though its legal effectiveness was limited).\n\nIn 1609 [[Gabriel B\u00e1thori]] granted new privileges to Turda. These were confirmed later by [[Gabriel Bethlen]].\nIn the battle of Turda, Ahmed Pasha defeated [[George II R\u00e1k\u00f3czi]] in 1659.\n\n===Modern times===\nIn 1711 the [[Principality of Transylvania (1711\u20131867)|Grand Principality of Translyvania]] was formed which became in 1804 part of the [[Austrian Empire]]. In 1867, by the [[Austro-Hungarian Compromise of 1867|Austro-Hungarian Compromise]], the city became again part of [[Kingdom of Hungary|Hungary]]. After the [[WWI|First World War]] following the proclamation of the [[Union of Transylvania with Romania]], Turda as well became part of [[Kingdom of Romania|Romania]] by the [[Treaty of Trianon]].<ref>{{in lang|ro}} [http://www.primariaturda.ro/index.php?topic=29&blank=0&pag=perioada_interbelica.htm \"Turda \u00een perioada interbelic\u0103\"] at the Turda City Hall site; accessed June 3, 2013</ref> In 1944, the [[Battle of Turda]] took place here, between [[German Army (Wehrmacht)|German]] and [[Hungarian Army|Hungarian]] forces on one side and [[Soviet Army|Soviet]] and [[Romanian Army|Romanian]] forces on the other. It was the largest battle fought in Transylvania during [[World War II]].\n\nFrom the late 1950s, Turda became a rather important industrial centre, housing factories for chemical, electrotechnical ceramics, cement, glass and steel cables. The nearby C\u00e2mpia Turzii town hosted a siderurgy (steel) plant. The city centre of Turda saw redevelopment in the late 1980s, including a House of Culture that hasn't been finished up to this date. Many houses in the historic center were demolished to create space for apartment buildings. The town's role of an industrial powerhouse has diminished from the 1990s onwards, but tourist attractions have kept the city in a good state up to today.{{citation needed|date=June 2019}}\n\n==Climate==\nTurda has a continental climate, characterised by warm dry summers and cold winters. The climate is influenced by the city's proximity to the Apuseni Mountains, as well as by urbanisation. Some West-Atlantic influences are present during winter and autumn. Winter temperatures are often below 0&nbsp;\u00b0C (32&nbsp;\u00b0F), even though they rarely drop below \u221210&nbsp;\u00b0C (14&nbsp;\u00b0F). On average, snow covers the ground for 65 days each winter. In summer, the average temperature is approximately 18&nbsp;\u00b0C (64&nbsp;\u00b0F) (the average for July and August), despite the fact that temperatures sometimes reach 35&nbsp;\u00b0C (95&nbsp;\u00b0F) to 40&nbsp;\u00b0C (104&nbsp;\u00b0F) in mid-summer in the city centre. Although average precipitation and humidity during summer is low, there are infrequent yet heavy and often violent storms. During spring and autumn, temperatures vary between 13&nbsp;\u00b0C (55&nbsp;\u00b0F) to 18&nbsp;\u00b0C (64&nbsp;\u00b0F), and precipitation during this time tends to be higher than in summer, with more frequent yet milder periods of rain.{{citation needed|date=August 2014}}\n\n==Demographics==\n{{Historical populations\n|source = Census data\n|1912 |13455\n|1930 |20023\n|1948 |25905\n|1956 |33614\n|1966 |42307\n|1977 |55294\n|1992 |61200\n|2002 |55770\n|2011 |47744\n}}\n\nAccording to the last [[Demographics of Romania|Romanian census]] from 2011 there were 47,744 people living within the city.\n\nOf this population, 84.7% are ethnic [[Romanians]], while 8.98% are ethnic [[Hungarian people|Hungarians]], 6.03% ethnic [[Romani people|Roma]] and 0.4% others.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.edrc.ro/recensamant.jsp?regiune_id=2140&judet_id=2295&localitate_id=2300|title=Structura Etno-demografic\u0103 a Rom\u00e2niei|website=Edrc.ro|accessdate=8 October 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Notable people==\n* [[Andreea Cacovean]] \n* [[Moise Drago\u0219]]\n* [[\u00c9tienne Hajd\u00fa]]\n* [[Baruch Kimmerling]]\n* [[Ecaterina Orb-Laz\u0103r]]\n* [[Alad\u00e1r L\u00e1szl\u00f3ffy]]\n* [[Csaba L\u00e1szl\u00f3ffy]]\n* [[Camil Mure\u0219anu]]\n* [[Mona Musc\u0103]]\n* [[Ion Ra\u021biu]]\n* [[Septimiu Sever]]\n\n==Tourism==\n* [[Salina Turda]]\n* [[Cheile Turzii]]\n\n==See also==\n{{portal|Poetry}}\n* [[Decree of Turda]]\n* [[Universitas Valachorum]]\n* [[List of Transylvanian Saxon localities]]\n* [[Ancient history of Transylvania]], [[History of Transylvania]]\n* [[Franziska Tesaurus]]\n* [[Edict of Torda]]\n\n==International relations==\n{{See also|List of twin towns and sister cities in Romania}}\n\n===Twin towns \u2013 sister cities===\nTurda is [[Twin towns and sister cities|twinned]] with:\n*{{flagicon|FRA}} [[Angoul\u00eame]]<ref name=\"Angoul\u00eame twinnings\">{{cite web | url = http://www.cncd.fr/frontoffice/bdd-region.asp?action=getRegion&id=21#tabs3 | title = National Commission for Decentralised cooperation | accessdate = 2013-12-26 | work = D\u00e9l\u00e9gation pour l\u2019Action Ext\u00e9rieure des Collectivit\u00e9s Territoriales (Minist\u00e8re des Affaires \u00e9trang\u00e8res) | language = French }}{{dead link|date=November 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n*{{flagicon|HUN}} [[H\u00f3dmez\u0151v\u00e1s\u00e1rhely]]\n*{{flagicon|ESP}} [[Santa Susanna, Catalonia|Santa Susanna]]\n*{{flagicon|SRB}} [[Torda (\u017diti\u0161te)|Torda]]\n\n==Picture gallery==\n<gallery>\nFile:PrimariaTurda02 2009.jpg|City Hall\nFile:VilaMendelTurda01.jpg|Mendel Villa\nFile:2010 - IMG 1176.jpg|Palace of Finance\nFile:Turda History Museum 2011-1.jpg|Princely Palace, now the History Museum\nFile:Turda Orthodox Cathedral1.JPG|Orthodox Cathedral\nFile:Salina Turda 5.jpg|[[Salina Turda|Turda salt mine]]\n</gallery>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n===Bibliography===\n*{{cite web|url=http://www.cimec.ro/scripts/muzee/iden.asp?k=214|title=INP - Museums and Collections in Romania|website=Cimec.ro|accessdate=October 8, 2017}}\n*{{cite web|url=http://www.britannica.com/eb/article-9073822/Turda|title=Turda - Romania|website=Britannica.com|accessdate=October 8, 2017}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Turda}}\n*{{in lang|ro}} [http://primariaturda.ro Official site of the city hall]\n* [http://www.turdaturism.ro TurdaTurism.ro]\n* [http://www.potaissa.org Fundatia Potaissa]\n\n{{Localities Cluj County}}\n\n{{Dacian cities}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Archaeological sites in Romania]]\n[[Category:Populated places in Cluj County]]\n[[Category:Cities in Romania]]\n[[Category:Turda]]\n[[Category:Roman sites in Romania]]\n[[Category:Roman towns and cities in Romania]]\n[[Category:Dacian towns]]\n[[Category:Mining communities in Romania]]\n[[Category:Capitals of former Romanian counties]]\n[[Category:Roman legionary fortresses in Romania]]\n", "text_old": "{{about||the former administrative subdivision of Romania|Turda County|the village in Tulcea County|Mihai Bravu, Tulcea}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=June 2012}}\n{{More citations needed|date=February 2007}}\n{{Infobox Romanian subdivision\n|type                   = municipality\n|county                 = Cluj\n|population_total       = auto\n|official_name                  = Turda\n|image_skyline                  = 2011-IMG 4425.jpg\n|image_caption                  = Republic Square\n|image_map              = Turda jud Cluj.png\n|map_caption            = Location in Cluj County\n|coordinates                    = {{coord|46|34|N|23|47|E|region:RO_type:city|display=inline,title}}\n|image_shield                   = Turda, Cluj COA.png\n|leader_name                    = Cristian-Octavian Matei<ref>[http://primariaturda.ro/primaria-turda/conducerea-primariei/cristian-octavian-matei/ primariaturda.ro]</ref>\n|leader_party                   = PNL\n|area_total_km2                 = 91.43\n|website                        = {{url|http://primariaturda.ro/}}\n}}\n\n'''Turda''' ({{IPA-ro|\u02c8turda}}; {{lang-de|link=no|Thorenburg}}; {{lang-hu|Torda}}; {{lang-la|Potaissa}}) is a [[Municipiu|city]] in [[Cluj County]], Romania, situated on the river [[Arie\u0219]].\n\n==History==\n\n===Ancient times===\n{{See also|Potaissa (castra)}}\n[[File:Milliarum of Aiton, modern copy erected in Turda, Romania in 1993.jpg|thumb|left|''Milliarium of Aiton'', the oldest known epigraphical attestation of Potaissa&nbsp;\u2013 a copy erected in June 1993 in front of the Turda Post Office]]\nThere is evidence of human settlement in the area dating to the [[Middle Paleolithic]], some 60,000 years ago.<ref>{{in lang|ro}} [http://www.primariaturda.ro/index.php?topic=29&blank=0&pag=comuna_primitiva.htm \"Comuna primitiv\u0103\"] at the Turda City Hall site; accessed March 21, 2013</ref> The [[Dacia]]ns established a town that [[Ptolemy]] in his [[Geography (Ptolemy)|''Geography'']] calls ''Patreuissa'', which is probably a corruption of ''Patavissa'' or ''Potaissa'', the latter being more common. It was conquered by the [[Ancient Rome|Romans]], who kept the name ''Potaissa'', between AD 101 and 106, during the rule of [[Trajan]], together with parts of [[Decebal]]'s [[Dacia]].<ref>{{in lang|ro}} [http://www.primariaturda.ro/index.php?topic=29&blank=0&pag=epoca_dacica.htm \"Epoca dacic\u0103\"] at the Turda City Hall site; accessed March 21, 2013</ref>\n\nThe name Potaissa is first recorded on a Roman [[milliarium]] discovered in 1758 in the nearby [[Aiton, Cluj|Aiton]] commune.<ref name=\"roman\">Lazarovici ''et al.'' 1997, pp. 202\u20133 (6.2 Cluj in the Old and Ancient Epochs)</ref>\n\n[[File:2006 0602Turda0088Potaissa.jpg|thumb|left|[[Roman bath]] at [[Potaissa (castra)|Castra Potaissa]]]]\n[[Milliarium of Aiton]] is an ancient Roman milestone dating from 108 AD, shortly after the [[Roman conquest of Dacia]], and showing the construction of the road from Potaissa to Napoca, by demand of the Emperor Trajan. It indicates the distance of {{convert|10000|ft|m}} (P.M.X.) to Potaissa. This is the first [[epigraphical]] attestation of the settlements of Potaissa and [[Napoca (ancient city)|Napoca]] in [[Roman Dacia]].\n\nThe complete inscription is: \"''Imp(erator)/ Caesar Nerva/ Traianus Aug(ustus)/ Germ(anicus) Dacicus/ pontif(ex) maxim(us)/ ''(sic)'' pot(estate) XII co(n)s(ul) V/ imp(erator) VI p(ater) p(atriae) fecit/ per coh(ortem) I Fl(aviam) Vlp(iam)/ Hisp(anam) mil(liariam) c(ivium) R(omanorum) eq(uitatam)/ a Potaissa Napo/cam / m(ilia) p(assuum) X''\". It was recorded in the ''[[Corpus Inscriptionum Latinarum]]'', vol.III, the 1627, Berlin, 1863.\n\nThis milliarium is an attestation of the road known to be built by ''[[Cohors I Hispanorum miliaria]]''.<ref>{{cite web |title=ARCHAEOLOGICAL REPERTORY OF ROMANIA. Archive Of The ''Vasile Parvan'' Institute Of Archaeology \u2013 Site Location Index |url=http://www.cimec.ro/scripts/arh/rar-index/sel.asp?nr=13&lang=en&nrsel=0&IDRap=1432#Lk1432 |accessdate=September 20, 2014 }}</ref>\n\nThe [[castrum]] established was named ''Potaissa'' too and became a [[municipium]], then a [[Colonia (Roman)|colonia]]. Potaissa was the basecamp of the [[Legio V Macedonica|Legio V ''Macedonica'']] from 166 to 274.\n\nThe [[Salina Turda|Potaissa salt mines]] were worked in the area since prehistoric times.\n\n===Middle Ages===\n{{See also|Transylvania in the Middle Ages}}\nAfter the [[Kingdom of Hungary|Hungarian]] conquest, the [[Salina Turda|Turda salt mines]] were first mentioned in 1075. They were closed in 1932 but have recently been reopened for tourism.\n\n[[Transylvanian Saxons|Saxons]] settled in the area in the 12th century. The town was destroyed during the Tartar invasion in 1241\u20131242. [[Andrew III of Hungary]] gave royal privileges to the settlement. These privileges were later confirmed by the [[Louis I of Hungary|Angevins of Hungary]].{{Citation needed|date=March 2010}}\n\nThe Hungarian Diet was held here in 1467, by [[Matthias Corvinus]]. Later, in the 16th century, Turda was often the residence of the [[Transylvanian Diet]], too. After the [[Battle of Moh\u00e1cs]], the city became part of the [[Eastern Hungarian Kingdom]] and since 1570 the [[Principality of Transylvania (1570\u20131711)|Principality of Transylvania]]. The 1558 Diet of Turda declared free practice of both the Catholic and [[Lutheranism|Lutheran]] religions. In 1563 the Diet also accepted the [[Calvinist]] religion, and in 1568 it extended freedom to all religions, declaring that \"It is not allowed to anybody to intimidate anybody with captivity or expelling for his religion\"&nbsp;\u2013 a freedom unusual in medieval Europe. This [[Edict of Turda]] is the first attempt at legislating general religious freedom in Christian Europe (though its legal effectiveness was limited).\n\nIn 1609 [[Gabriel B\u00e1thori]] granted new privileges to Turda. These were confirmed later by [[Gabriel Bethlen]].\nIn the battle of Turda, Ahmed Pasha defeated [[George II R\u00e1k\u00f3czi]] in 1659.\n\n===Modern times===\nIn 1711 the [[Principality of Transylvania (1711\u20131867)|Grand Principality of Translyvania]] was formed which became in 1804 part of the [[Austrian Empire]]. In 1867, by the [[Austro-Hungarian Compromise of 1867|Austro-Hungarian Compromise]], the city became again part of [[Kingdom of Hungary|Hungary]]. After the [[WWI|First World War]] following the proclamation of the [[Union of Transylvania with Romania]], Turda as well became part of [[Kingdom of Romania|Romania]] by the [[Treaty of Trianon]].<ref>{{in lang|ro}} [http://www.primariaturda.ro/index.php?topic=29&blank=0&pag=perioada_interbelica.htm \"Turda \u00een perioada interbelic\u0103\"] at the Turda City Hall site; accessed June 3, 2013</ref> In 1944, the [[Battle of Turda]] took place here, between [[German Army (Wehrmacht)|German]] and [[Hungarian Army|Hungarian]] forces on one side and [[Soviet Army|Soviet]] and [[Romanian Army|Romanian]] forces on the other. It was the largest battle fought in Transylvania during [[World War II]].\n\nFrom the late 1950s, Turda became a rather important industrial centre, housing factories for chemical, electrotechnical ceramics, cement, glass and steel cables. The nearby C\u00e2mpia Turzii town hosted a siderurgy (steel) plant. The city centre of Turda saw redevelopment in the late 1980s, including a House of Culture that hasn't been finished up to this date. Many houses in the historic center were demolished to create space for apartment buildings. The town's role of an industrial powerhouse has diminished from the 1990s onwards, but tourist attractions have kept the city in a good state up to today.{{citation needed|date=June 2019}}\n\n==Climate==\nTurda has a continental climate, characterised by warm dry summers and cold winters. The climate is influenced by the city's proximity to the Apuseni Mountains, as well as by urbanisation. Some West-Atlantic influences are present during winter and autumn. Winter temperatures are often below 0&nbsp;\u00b0C (32&nbsp;\u00b0F), even though they rarely drop below \u221210&nbsp;\u00b0C (14&nbsp;\u00b0F). On average, snow covers the ground for 65 days each winter. In summer, the average temperature is approximately 18&nbsp;\u00b0C (64&nbsp;\u00b0F) (the average for July and August), despite the fact that temperatures sometimes reach 35&nbsp;\u00b0C (95&nbsp;\u00b0F) to 40&nbsp;\u00b0C (104&nbsp;\u00b0F) in mid-summer in the city centre. Although average precipitation and humidity during summer is low, there are infrequent yet heavy and often violent storms. During spring and autumn, temperatures vary between 13&nbsp;\u00b0C (55&nbsp;\u00b0F) to 18&nbsp;\u00b0C (64&nbsp;\u00b0F), and precipitation during this time tends to be higher than in summer, with more frequent yet milder periods of rain.{{citation needed|date=August 2014}}\n\n==Demographics==\n{{Historical populations\n|source = Census data\n|1912 |13455\n|1930 |20023\n|1948 |25905\n|1956 |33614\n|1966 |42307\n|1977 |55294\n|1992 |61200\n|2002 |55770\n|2011 |47744\n}}\n\nAccording to the last [[Demographics of Romania|Romanian census]] from 2011 there were 47,744 people living within the city.\n\nOf this population, 84.7% are ethnic [[Romanians]], while 8.98% are ethnic [[Hungarian people|Hungarians]], 6.03% ethnic [[Romani people|Roma]] and 0.4% others.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.edrc.ro/recensamant.jsp?regiune_id=2140&judet_id=2295&localitate_id=2300|title=Structura Etno-demografic\u0103 a Rom\u00e2niei|website=Edrc.ro|accessdate=8 October 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Notable people==\n* [[Andreea Cacovean]] \n* [[Moise Drago\u0219]]\n* [[\u00c9tienne Hajd\u00fa]]\n* [[Baruch Kimmerling]]\n* [[Ecaterina Orb-Laz\u0103r]]\n* [[Alad\u00e1r L\u00e1szl\u00f3ffy]]\n* [[Csaba L\u00e1szl\u00f3ffy]]\n* [[Camil Mure\u0219anu]]\n* [[Mona Musc\u0103]]\n* [[Ion Ra\u021biu]]\n* [[Septimiu Sever]]\n\n==Tourism==\n* [[Salina Turda]]\n* [[Cheile Turzii]]\n\n==See also==\n{{portal|Poetry}}\n* [[Decree of Turda]]\n* [[Universitas Valachorum]]\n* [[List of Transylvanian Saxon localities]]\n* [[Ancient history of Transylvania]], [[History of Transylvania]]\n* [[Franziska Tesaurus]]\n* [[Edict of Torda]]\n\n==International relations==\n{{See also|List of twin towns and sister cities in Romania}}\n\n===Twin towns \u2013 sister cities===\nTurda is [[Twin towns and sister cities|twinned]] with:\n*{{flagicon|FRA}} [[Angoul\u00eame]]<ref name=\"Angoul\u00eame twinnings\">{{cite web | url = http://www.cncd.fr/frontoffice/bdd-region.asp?action=getRegion&id=21#tabs3 | title = National Commission for Decentralised cooperation | accessdate = 2013-12-26 | work = D\u00e9l\u00e9gation pour l\u2019Action Ext\u00e9rieure des Collectivit\u00e9s Territoriales (Minist\u00e8re des Affaires \u00e9trang\u00e8res) | language = French }}{{dead link|date=November 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n*{{flagicon|HUN}} [[H\u00f3dmez\u0151v\u00e1s\u00e1rhely]]\n*{{flagicon|ESP}} [[Santa Susanna, Catalonia|Santa Susanna]]\n*{{flagicon|SRB}} [[Torda (\u017diti\u0161te)|Torda]]\n\n==Picture gallery==\n<gallery>\nFile:PrimariaTurda02 2009.jpg