2|{{flagicon|New Zealand|size=50px}}\n|-\n|25 May\n|[[Sydney Cricket Ground|SCG]], [[Sydney]]\n|align=center|11\u201325\n|-\n|rowspan=3 |{{flagicon|New Zealand}} [[1955 Australia rugby union tour of New Zealand|1955]]\n|17 September\n|[[Eden Park]], [[Auckland]]\n|rowspan=3 align=right|{{ru-rt|New Zealand}}\n|align=center|3\u20138\n|rowspan=3|{{ru|Australia}}\n|rowspan=3|{{flagicon|New Zealand|size=50px}}\n|-\n|3 September\n|[[Carisbrook]], [[Dunedin]]\n|align=center|8\u20130\n|-\n|20 August\n|[[Athletic Park, Wellington|Athletic Park]], [[Wellington]]\n|align=center|16\u20138\n|-\n|rowspan=2 |{{flagicon|New Zealand}} [[1952 Australia rugby union tour of New Zealand|1952]]\n|13 September\n|[[Athletic Park, Wellington|Athletic Park]], [[Wellington]]\n|rowspan=2 align=right|{{ru-rt|New Zealand}}\n|align=center|15\u20138\n|rowspan=2|{{ru|Australia}}\n|rowspan=2 align=center|''Draw''\n|-\n|6 September\n|[[Lancaster Park]], [[Christchurch]]\n|align=center|9\u201314\n|-\n|rowspan=3|{{flagicon|Australia}} [[1951 New Zealand rugby union tour of Australia|1951]]\n|21 July\n|[[The Gabba]], [[Brisbane]]\n|rowspan=3 align=right|{{ru-rt|Australia}}\n|align=center|6\u201316\n|rowspan=3|{{ru|New Zealand}}\n|rowspan=3|{{flagicon|New Zealand|size=50px}}\n|-\n|7 July\n|[[Sydney Cricket Ground|SCG]], [[Sydney]]\n|align=center|11\u201317\n|-\n|23 June\n|[[Sydney Cricket Ground|SCG]], [[Sydney]]\n|align=center|0\u20138\n|-\n|rowspan=2|{{flagicon|New Zealand}} [[1949 Australia rugby union tour of New Zealand|1949]]\n|24 September\n|[[Eden Park]], [[Auckland]]\n|rowspan=2 align=right|{{ru-rt|New Zealand}}\n|align=center|9\u201316\n|rowspan=2|{{ru|Australia}}\n|rowspan=2|{{flagicon|Australia|size=50px}}\n|-\n|3 September\n|[[Athletic Park, Wellington|Athletic Park]], [[Wellington]]\n|align=center|6\u201311\n|-\n|rowspan=2|{{flagicon|Australia}} [[1947 New Zealand rugby union tour of Australia|1947]]\n|28 June\n|[[Sydney Cricket Ground|SCG]], [[Sydney]]\n|rowspan=2 align=right|{{ru-rt|Australia}}\n|align=center|14\u201327\n|rowspan=2|{{ru|New Zealand}}\n|rowspan=2|{{flagicon|New Zealand|size=50px}}\n|-\n|14 June\n|[[Brisbane Showgrounds|Exhibition Ground]], [[Brisbane]]\n|align=center|5\u201313\n|-\n|rowspan=2 |{{flagicon|New Zealand}} [[1946 Australia rugby union tour of New Zealand|1946]]\n|28 September\n|[[Eden Park]], [[Auckland]]\n|rowspan=2 align=right|{{ru-rt|New Zealand}}\n|align=center|14\u201310\n|rowspan=2|{{ru|Australia}}\n|rowspan=2|{{flagicon|New Zealand|size=50px}}\n|-\n|14 September\n|[[Carisbrook]], [[Dunedin]]\n|align=center|31\u20138\n|-\n|rowspan=3|{{flagicon|Australia}} [[1938 New Zealand rugby union tour of Australia|1938]]\n|13 August\n|[[Sydney Cricket Ground|SCG]], [[Sydney]]\n|rowspan=3 align=right|{{ru-rt|Australia}}\n|align=center|6\u201314\n|rowspan=3|{{ru|New Zealand}}\n|rowspan=3|{{flagicon|New Zealand|size=50px}}\n|-\n|6 August\n|[[Brisbane Showgrounds|Exhibition Ground]], [[Brisbane]]\n|align=center|14\u201320\n|-\n|23 July\n|[[Sydney Cricket Ground|SCG]], [[Sydney]]\n|align=center|9\u201324\n|-\n|rowspan=2 |{{flagicon|New Zealand}} [[1936 Australia rugby union tour of New Zealand|1936]]\n|12 September\n|[[Carisbrook]], [[Dunedin]]\n|rowspan=2 align=right|{{ru-rt|New Zealand}}\n|align=center|38\u201313\n|rowspan=2|{{ru|Australia}}\n|rowspan=2|{{flagicon|New Zealand|size=50px}}\n|-\n|5 September\n|[[Athletic Park, Wellington|Athletic Park]], [[Wellington]]\n|align=center|11\u20136\n|-\n|rowspan=2 |{{flagicon|Australia}} [[1934 New Zealand rugby union tour of Australia|1934]]\n|25 August\n|[[Sydney Cricket Ground|SCG]], [[Sydney]]\n|rowspan=2 align=right|{{ru-rt|Australia}}\n|align=center|3\u20133\n|rowspan=2|{{ru|New Zealand}}\n|rowspan=2|{{flagicon|Australia|size=50px}}\n|-\n|11 August\n|[[Sydney Cricket Ground|SCG]], [[Sydney]]\n|align=center|25\u201311\n|-\n|rowspan=3|{{flagicon|Australia}} [[1932 New Zealand rugby union tour of Australia|1932]]\n|23 July\n|[[Sydney Cricket Ground|SCG]], [[Sydney]]\n|rowspan=3 align=right|{{ru-rt|Australia}}\n|align=center|13\u201321\n|rowspan=3|{{ru|New Zealand}}\n|rowspan=3|{{flagicon|New Zealand|size=50px}}\n|-\n|16 July\n|[[Brisbane Showgrounds|Exhibition Ground]], [[Brisbane]]\n|align=center|3\u201321\n|-\n|2 July\n|[[Sydney Cricket Ground|SCG]], [[Sydney]]\n|align=center|22\u201317\n|-\n|}\n\n==Overall==\n'''Most titles won:'''\n# New Zealand - 47 (+1 in 1931)\n# Australia - 12\n\n''Longest time held by Australia:'' 5 years (1998\u20132002) (5 Titles)\n\n''Longest time held by New Zealand:'' 28\nyears (1951\u20131978) (12 Titles)\n\n'''Home Series Wins:'''\n# New Zealand - 15\n# Australia - 5\n\n'''Away Series Wins:'''\n# New Zealand - 12\n# Australia - 2\n\n'''Home and Away Series Wins:'''\n# New Zealand - 21\n# Australia - 5\n\nAs of: 2019\n\n==Matches==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!rowspan=2|Venue\n!rowspan=2|Played\n!colspan=2|Won by\n!rowspan=2|Drawn\n!colspan=2|Total points\n|-\n!align=center|{{ru|Australia}}\n!align=center|{{ru|New Zealand}}\n!Australia\n!NZ\n|-\n| align=left|{{flagicon|Australia}} Australia\n| 70\n| 22\n| 43\n| 5\n| 1204\n| 1516\n|-\n| align=left|{{flagicon|New Zealand}} New Zealand\n|70\n| 14\n| 55\n| 1\n|  895\n| 1605\n|-\n| Neutral venue\n| 4\n| 1\n| 3\n| 0\n|  79\n| 112\n|-\n!Overall\n!144\n!37\n!101\n!6\n!2178\n!3233\n|-\n|}\n\nAs of: Aug 17, 2019\n\n==Venues==\n===In Australia===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Stadium !! City !! State !! Won by<br>{{ru|Australia}} !! Won by<br>{{ru|New Zealand}} !! Draw\n|-\n| [[Sydney Cricket Ground]]\n| rowspan=4|[[Sydney]]\n| rowspan=4|{{flag|New South Wales}}\n| align=center|6\n| align=center|13\n| align=center|1\n|-\n| [[Concord Oval]]\n| align=center|0\n| align=center|3\n| align=center|0\n|-\n| [[Sydney Football Stadium]]\n| align=center|4\n| align=center|2\n| align=center|0\n|-\n| [[Stadium Australia]]\n| align=center|6\n| align=center|10\n| align=center|1\n|-\n| [[Brisbane Showgrounds|Brisbane Exhibition Ground]]\n| rowspan=4|[[Brisbane]]\n| rowspan=4|{{flag|Queensland}}\n| align=center|0\n| align=center|5\n| align=center|0\n|-\n| [[The Gabba]]\n| align=center|0\n| align=center|1\n| align=center|0\n|-\n| [[Ballymore Stadium]]\n| align=center|1\n| align=center|3\n| align=center|2\n|-\n| [[Lang Park]]\n| align=center|2\n| align=center|4\n| align=center|1\n|-\n| [[Melbourne Cricket Ground]]\n| rowspan=2|[[Melbourne]]\n| rowspan=2|{{flag|Victoria}}\n| align=center|2\n| align=center|1\n| align=center|0\n|-\n| [[Docklands Stadium]]\n| align=center|0\n| align=center|1\n| align=center|0\n|-\n| [[Perth Stadium]]\n| [[Perth]]\n| {{flag|Western Australia}}\n| align=center|1\n| align=center|0\n| align=center|0\n|-\n|colspan=3|\n| align=center|22\n| align=center|43\n| align=center|5\n|}\n\n===In New Zealand===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Stadium !! City !! Island !! Won by<br>{{ru|New Zealand}} !! Won by<br>{{ru|Australia}} !! Draw\n|-\n| [[Eden Park]]\n| rowspan=2|[[Auckland]]\n| rowspan=2|[[North Island|North]]\n| align=center|24\n| align=center|4\n| align=center|0\n|-\n| [[Epsom, New Zealand|Epsom Showgrounds]]\n| align=center|1\n| align=center|0\n| align=center|0\n|-\n| [[Athletic Park, Wellington|Athletic Park]]\n| rowspan=2|[[Wellington]]\n| rowspan=2|[[North Island|North]]\n| align=center|8\n| align=center|5\n| align=center|1\n|-\n| [[Wellington Regional Stadium]]\n| align=center|4\n| align=center|1\n| align=center|0\n|-\n| [[Carisbrook]]\n| rowspan=2|[[Dunedin]]\n| rowspan=2|[[South Island|South]]\n| align=center|8\n| align=center|1\n| align=center|0\n|-\n| [[Forsyth Barr Stadium]]\n| align=center|2\n| align=center|0\n| align=center|0\n|-\n| [[Lancaster Park]]\n| [[Christchurch]]\n| [[South Island|South]]\n| align=center|9\n| align=center|3\n| align=center|0\n|-\n| colspan=3|\n| align=center|56\n| align=center|14\n| align=center|1\n|-\n|}\n\n==By year==\n{{details|History of rugby union matches between Australia and New Zealand}}\n\n==Women's format==\nIn 2018 edition, [[Black Ferns]] and [[Wallaroos]] played Tests as curtain-raisers to both Bledisloe Cup Tests in [[Sydney]] and [[Auckland]]. The crowd at the end of both women's Tests swelled to about 28,000. The women's double-header concept was deemed as a success by NZR CEO [[Steve Tew]] who is open to repeating the concept. For the equivalent match at [[Eden Park]] in 2016, also before the men's clash, the crowd size peaked at 12,500.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.espn.com/rugby/story/_/id/24487106/bledisloe-cup-japan-fixture-suffer-all-blacks-win-series|title=Bledisloe Cup Japan fixture could suffer after All Blacks win series|date=27 August 2018 |work=[[ESPN Scrum]] |accessdate=6 February 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Media coverage==\nIn Australia, the Bledisloe Cup was televised between 1992 and 1995 by [[Network Ten]]. Since 1996, [[Fox Sports (Australia)|Fox Sports]] has televised it jointly with [[Seven Network]] between 1996 and 2010, [[Nine Network]] in 2011 and 2012 and Network Ten since 2013.\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Sports|Australia|New Zealand}}\n*[[History of rugby union matches between Australia and New Zealand]]\n*[[Laurie O'Reilly Cup]]\n*[[Rugby union trophies and awards]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Rugby union national trophies and awards}}\n{{Australia national rugby union team}}\n{{New Zealand national rugby union team}}\n{{History of Tier 1 nations}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bledisloe Cup}}\n[[Category:History of rugby union matches between Australia and New Zealand]]\n[[Category:International rugby union competitions hosted by Australia]]\n[[Category:International rugby union competitions hosted by New Zealand]]\n[[Category:1931 establishments in Australia]]\n[[Category:1931 establishments in New Zealand]]\n[[Category:The Rugby Championship trophies]]\n[[Category:Recurring sporting events established in 1931]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2016}}\n{{Infobox rugby league football competition\n| current_season =\n| logo           = Bledisloe Cup on display in Sydney 2014.jpg\n| alt            = \n| pixels         = 200 px\n| caption        = Bledisloe Cup on display in Sydney 2014.\n| sport          = Rugby union\n| founded        = 1931\n| teams          = 2 \n| countrytag     = \n| country        = {{ru|Australia}}<br>{{ru|New Zealand}}\n| gov_body       = \n| championtag    = \n| champion       = {{ru|New Zealand}}\n| season         = 2019\n| next host      = \n| most_champs    = {{ru|New Zealand}}\n| count          = 48\n| website        = \n| current        = \n}}\n\nThe '''Bledisloe Cup''' is a [[rugby union]] competition between the national teams of [[Australia national rugby union team|Australia]] and [[New Zealand national rugby union team|New Zealand]] that has been contested since the 1930s. The frequency at which the competition is held has varied, as has the number of matches played, but it currently consists of an annual three-match series, reduced to a two-match series in [[Rugby World Cup|World Cup]] years, with two of the matches also counting towards [[The Rugby Championship]]. New Zealand have had the most success, winning the trophy in 2019 for the 47th time (excluding the disputed inaugural competition in 1931), while Australia have won the trophy 12 times.\n\n==History==\n[[File:Bledisloe Cup with fans on display in Sydney 2014.jpg|250 px|thumb|left|Bledisloe Cup Festival Day 2014 in Sydney]]\nThere is some dispute as to when the first Bledisloe Cup match was played. The [[Australian Rugby Union]] (ARU) contend that the one-off 1931 match played at [[Eden Park]] was first. However, no firm evidence has been produced to support this claim, and it is recorded in the minutes of a New Zealand union management meeting several days later that [[Charles Bathurst, 1st Viscount Bledisloe|Lord Bledisloe]] wished to present a cup for the All Blacks and Wallabies to play for. The [[New Zealand Rugby Union]] (NZRU) believe that the first match was when New Zealand toured Australia in 1932.\n\nBetween 1931 and 1981, the Bledisloe Cup was contested irregularly in the course of rugby tours between the two countries, with New Zealand winning it 19 times and Australia four times; in 1949, Australia won the competition for the first time on New Zealand soil. The trophy itself was apparently 'lost' during this period and reportedly rediscovered in a Melbourne store room. It was contested annually from 1982 to 1995, sometimes as a series of three matches (two in 1995) and other times in a single match. During these years, New Zealand won the trophy 11 times and Australia three times.\n\nSince 1996, the cup has been contested as part of the annual [[Tri Nations (rugby union)|Tri Nations]] tournament. Until 1998, the cup was contested in a three-match series consisting of the two Tri Nations matches between the two sides and a third match. New Zealand won the series in 1996 and 1997, and Australia won it in 1998.\n\nIn 1996, and from 1999 through 2005, the third match was not played; during these years, Australia and New Zealand played each other twice as part of the Tri Nations for the cup. If the two teams won one game each, or if both games were drawn, the cup was retained by its current holder. The non-holder needed to win the two games 2\u20130 or 1\u20130 (with a draw) to regain the cup. A criticism of this system was that, with the two sides being very well matched in ability level, it was very common for the teams to win one game each and many rugby fans were dissatisfied with one team keeping the cup in the years when the series was tied at 1\u20131 (1999, 2000, 2002, 2004).\n\nIn 2006, the Tri Nations series was extended so that each team played each other three times, meaning a return of the three-game contest for the Bledisloe Cup. However, the cup reverted to the two-game contest in 2007 because the [[2007 Tri Nations Series|Tri Nations]] was abbreviated that year to minimise interference with the teams' preparations for the [[2007 Rugby World Cup|World Cup]].\n\nThe three-match format for the Bledisloe Cup continued in 2012, with the first two matches taking place as part of the [[2012 Rugby Championship]].\n\n==Neutral venues==\n===Hong Kong===\nIn 2008 it was announced that the Bledisloe Cup would be contested over an unprecedented four matches, with three games played in Australia and New Zealand and a fourth and potentially deciding game in [[Hong Kong]] in an effort to promote the game in [[Asia]] (the first time Australia and New Zealand played in a third country outside the [[Rugby World Cup]]).<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/rugby_union/7274401.stm |title=Hong Kong to host NZ v Australia |work=BBC Sport |date=3 March 2008 |accessdate=2008-03-03}}</ref> The Hong Kong match, which drew a crowd of 39,000 to see the All Blacks (who had already clinched the Bledisloe Cup) defeat the Wallabies 19\u201314,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/rugby_union/7694689.stm |title=Australia 14\u201319 New Zealand |work=BBC Sport |date=1 November 2008 |accessdate=2008-11-08}}</ref> proved to be a financial success for the two unions, generating a reported [[pound sterling|\u00a3]]5.5&nbsp;million.<ref name=\"US-Japan\">{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/rugby_union/7701536.stm |title=US & Japan may host Bledisloe Cup |work=BBC Sport |date=31 October 2008 |accessdate=2008-11-08}}</ref> A 2010 fourth match was again set in [[Hong Kong Stadium]] but failed to attract sufficient ticket sales.<ref name=\"ODT_126226\">{{cite web |url=http://www.odt.co.nz/sport/rugby/126226/rugby-bledisloe-test-locked-hong-kong |title=Rugby: Bledisloe test locked in for Hong Kong |date=13 September 2010 |work=[[Otago Daily Times]] |accessdate=20 September 2011}}</ref>\n\n===Japan===\nThe capital [[Tokyo]] hosted a fourth Bledisloe Test match on 31 October 2009. Each team expected to clear at least [[Australian dollar|A$]]3.8&nbsp;million/[[New Zealand dollar|NZ$]]5&nbsp;million from the Tokyo match.<ref name=\"2009 Tokyo\">{{cite news|url=http://www.theroar.com.au/2009/10/29/fourth-bledisloe-cup-test-is-a-good-thing-for-rugby/|title=Wallabies to take on All Blacks in Tokyo|last=AAP|date=1 July 2009|publisher=The Roar|accessdate=2016-07-18}}</ref>\n\nOn 27 October 2018, Bledisloe Cup returned to Japan for the second time and was hosted in [[Yokohama]] with the purpose of promoting and preparing for [[2019 Rugby World Cup]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://mainichi.jp/english/articles/20181028/p2g/00m/0sp/013000c|title=Rugby: NZ beats Australia 37-20 to sweep Bledisloe Cup series|date=28 October 2018 |work=[[Mainichi]] |accessdate=6 February 2019}}</ref> All Blacks beating Wallabies 37-20 in the third test to sweep the series. The attendance figures was around 46,000 which became the record for a rugby test match in Japan.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://english.kyodonews.net/news/2018/10/fa13a871f4c3-rugby-japan-special-venue-for-world-cup-all-blacks-captain-says.html|title=Rugby: Japan 'special' venue for World Cup, All Blacks captain says|date=27 October 2018 |work=[[Kyodo News]] |accessdate=6 February 2019}}</ref> The relatively poor ticket sales included about 10% arrived via giveaways because of clashing with the fixture between [[Japan national rugby team|Japan]] and [[World XV]] a day before in [[Osaka]] and lack of competitiveness of Wallabies contributing to dead rubber match of the series.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.japantimes.co.jp/sports/2018/10/26/rugby/capacity-crowd-not-expected-bledisloe-cup-test/|title=Capacity crowd not expected for Bledisloe Cup test|date=26 October 2018 |work=[[Japan Times]] |accessdate=6 February 2019}}</ref>\n\n===United States===\nBefore the first match in Hong Kong, the two countries' rugby federations were considering taking Cup matches to the [[United States]] and [[Japan]] in 2009 and 2010. However, the proposed match in USA did not come to fruition.\n\n==Future proposals==\nBehind the push from [[World Rugby]] with their League of Nations concept, only one match result would count for League of Nations points but the new season schedule must be able to accommodate a second Test each year in the new format. The gate receipts from Bledisloe Cup match ups are critical to both [[Rugby Australia]] and [[New Zealand Rugby Union]] and both nations are firm in their belief that one home match is mandatory. The third Bledisloe, which has long been a cash cow for both nations, could cease to exist. Any cash lost from forfeiting that match would be compensated by [[Australian dollar|A$]]18 million per year in League of Nations broadcast revenue.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.smh.com.au/sport/rugby-union/rugby-championship-change-likely-as-world-league-talks-gain-steam-20190205-p50vui.html|title=Rugby Championship change likely as World League talks gain steam|last=Phillips|first=Sam|work=[[The Sydney Morning Herald]]|date=5 February 2019|accessdate=6 February 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Results==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Date\n! Venue\n! Home\n! Score\n! Away\n! Trophy<br>Winner\n|-\n|rowspan=3 align=center|2020<ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.rugby.com.au/news/2020/01/30/wallabies-south-africa-new-zealand-perth|title=Wallabies to return to Perth in 2020, 2021|date=30 January 2020|website=www.rugby.com.au|accessdate=6 February 2020}}</ref>\n|17 October\n|[[Lang Park|Suncorp Stadium]], [[Brisbane]]\n|align=right|{{ru-rt|Australia}}\n|align=center|\u2013\n|{{ru|New Zealand}}\n|rowspan=3|\n|-\n|15 August\n|[[Wellington Regional Stadium|Sky Stadium]], [[Wellington]]\n|align=right|{{ru-rt|New Zealand}}\n|align=center|\u2013\n|{{ru|Australia}}\n|-\n|8 August\n|[[Docklands Stadium|Marvel Stadium]], [[Melbourne]]\n|align=right|{{ru-rt|Australia}}\n|align=center|\u2013\n|{{ru|New Zealand}}\n|-\n|rowspan=2 align=center|2019\n|17 August\n|[[Eden Park]], [[Auckland]]\n|align=right|{{ru-rt|New Zealand}}\n|align=center|36\u20130\n|{{ru|Australia}}\n|rowspan=2|{{flagicon|New Zealand|size=50px}}\n|-\n|10 August\n|[[Optus Stadium]], [[Perth Australia|Perth]]\n|align=right|